Let G be a Group. Let H\leq  G be a Subgroup of G. Let A\subseteq  G be a subset of G. Let U_{H} be the subset of G equal to the elements of H. Then we define:

AH to be the subset of G equal to AU_{H}

HA to be the subset of G equal to U_{H}A

Let G be a Group. Let g\in G be an element. We define the Conjugacy Class of g to be the subset \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g) of G equal to \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g)=\{g^{b}\in G\mid b\in G\}. In other words, \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g) is the set of elements a\in G such that a is conjugate to g.

Let G be a Group. Let a\in G and b\in G be elements of G. Then \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a)=\mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b) iff \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a)\cap \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b)
eq \emptyset .

(\Longrightarrow ) Assume \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a)=\mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b). Then \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a)\cap \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b)
eq \emptyset .

(\Longleftarrow ) Assume \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a)\cap \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b)
eq \emptyset . Then there exists an element x of G such that x\in \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a) and x\in \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b).

We see that \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a)\subseteq \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b): for any y\in \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a), we see y is conjugate to a and a is conjugate to x and x is conjugate to b. Then b is conjugate to y by Conjugation forms an equivalence relation. Hence y\in \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b), which proves \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a)\subseteq \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b).

We see that \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b)\subseteq \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a): let y\in \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b) be arbitrary. Then y is conjugate to b and b is conjugate to x and x is conjugate to a, which means y is conjugate to a by Conjugation forms an equivalence relation. Hence y\in \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a), which establishes \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (b)\subseteq \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (a).

Moreover, this forms a partition of G in the sense that for any g\in G there exists exactly one conjugacy class C such that g\in C. This is because g\in \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g) and for any h\in G such that g\in \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (h) must satisfy \mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g)=\mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (h) by Extension problem.

Let G be a Group, let A\subseteq  G be a subset. We define the Normalizer of A to be the subgroup N_{G}(A) such that
N_{G}(A)=\{h\in  G\mid  Ah=hA\}
In other words, for any a\in  A and for any h\in  N_{G}(A), we have h^{-1}ah\in  A.

We see
\begin {align}1_{H}\varphi (1_{G})&=\varphi (1_{G})\\ &=\varphi (1_{G}1_{G})\\ &=\varphi (1_{G})\varphi (1_{G})\end {align}
and then the Cancellation law gives the result.

We see that
\begin {align}\varphi (g^{-1})\varphi (g) &= \varphi (g^{-1}g)\\ &= \varphi (1_{G})\\ &= 1_{H}\end {align}
then multiplying both sides on the right by \varphi (g)^{-1} gives the result.

Consider the subgroup H\leq \mathop {\textrm {GL}}\nolimits _{2}(\mathbb {C}) generated by powers and products of
A=\begin {pmatrix}0 & 1\\-1 & 0\end {pmatrix},\quad \hbox {and}\quad  B=\begin {pmatrix}0 & \mathrm {i}\\\mathrm {i} & 0\end {pmatrix}
where \mathrm {i}^{2}=-1. (We see A^{4} is the identity matrix, and B^{4} is the identity matrix.) Then H is isomorphic to Quaternion Group Q_{8}.

Let \{\mathcal {F}_{i}\}_{i\in  I} be a family of groups. We define the Product Group \prod _{i\in  I}\mathcal {F}_{i} whose underlying set is the product of the underlying sets of the family, where the binary operator is defined by, for any g,h\in  \prod _{i\in  I}\mathcal {F}_{i},
(gh)_{i}=g_{i}h_{i}
When I=\{1,2\}, this recovers Product group.

Let \{\mathcal {F}_{i}\}_{i\in  I} be a family of groups. We define the Direct Sum \bigoplus _{i\in  I}\mathcal {F}_{i} whose underlying set is the product of the underlying sets of the family where only finitely many components are not the identity element, where the binary operator is defined by, for any g,h\in  \prod _{i\in  I}\mathcal {F}_{i},
(gh)_{i}=g_{i}h_{i}
For I being a finite indexing set, this coincides with Product of family of groups.

Let A, B, C be Groups. Let \mathbf {1} be the trivial group. A Short Exact Sequence describes
\mathbf {1}\to  A\xrightarrow {f} B\xrightarrow {g}C\to \mathbf {1}
where f\colon  A\to  B and g\colon  B\to  C are Group Morphisms such that \mathop {\textrm {Im}}\nolimits (f)=\ker (g).

Problem: find which groups G fit a short exact sequence
\mathbf {1}\to  H\to  G\xrightarrow {\pi }K\to \mathbf {1}
where K\cong  G/\ker (\pi ) and \ker (\pi )\cong  H.

Let G and H be Groups. We say a group \widehat {G} is a Extension of G by H if there is a short exact sequence
\mathbf {1}\to  H\to \widehat {G}\xrightarrow {\pi }G\to \mathbf {1}
where \pi \colon \widehat {G}\to  G is a surjective group morphism such that \widehat {G}/\ker (\pi )\cong  G.

Let G and H be Groups. Let \widehat {G}_{1} and \widehat {G}_{2} be extensions of G by H. A Morphism of Extensions is a morphism \varphi \colon \widehat {G}_{1}\to \widehat {G}_{2} such that
\begin {array}{ccccccccc} \mathbf {1} & \to  & H & \to  & \widehat {G}_{1} & \to  & G & \to  & \mathbf {1}\\            &     & \parallel  & & \downarrow ^{\varphi } & & \parallel  & & \\ \mathbf {1} & \to  & H & \to  & \widehat {G}_{2} & \to  & G & \to  & \mathbf {1} \end {array}
commutes.

Let H, G, \widehat {G} be Groups. Let
\mathbf {1}\to  H\to  \widehat {G}\xrightarrow {\pi }G\to \mathbf {1}
be a short exact sequence. We say the extension \widehat {G} is Split if there is a group morphism \sigma \colon  G\to \widehat {G} such that \pi \circ \sigma =\mathop {\textrm {id}}\nolimits _{G}.

Let G be a Group, let X be a set, suppose G acts on X. Let x\in  X be arbitrary. The function
\begin {split}\overline {f}\colon  &G/G_{x}\to  G\cdot  x\\ &gG_{x}\mapsto  g\cdot  x\end {split}
is a bijection between the left cosets G/G_{x} and the orbit G\cdot  x.

Let \chi =\{G\cdot g\mid g\in G\} be the set of orbits. Since the Conjugacy Classes of a group partitions G, we see |G|=\sum _{G\cdot g\in \chi }|\mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g)|. and the conjugacy classes of elements z\in Z(G) of the center is C(z)=\{z\}, we see that |G|=\sum _{g\in Z(G)}|\mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g)| + \sum _{\substack {G\cdot g\in \chi \ g
otin Z(G)}}|\mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g)|=|Z(G)| + \sum _{\substack {G\cdot g\in \chi \ g
otin Z(G)}}|\mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g)|. Hence the result since we proved |\mathop {	extrm {Cl}}
olimits (g)|=[G : C_{G}(g)].
